				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The FIR is like taking the input signal, then adding several versions of it together, each offset by one sample, and with each one's gain adjusted separately. So you have the input signal, the input delayed by one sample, delayed by two samples, up to delayed by 7 samples.<br /><br />If you add just the first, you get the original. If you add the first and second at equal gains, you get a lowpass, since a waveform of say +0.5, -0.5, +0.5, -0.5... would get nullified when added to a shifted version of itself. But if you add the original at 1.0 gain, and the delayed-by-one-sample version at -1.0 gain, you intensify the highest frequencies (and do the opposite to low frequencies, since they only slow change).<br /><br />Jarhmander, are you sure you don't get more resolution from an 8-point FIR? Remember that it doesn't have to be symmetrical since the phase response can be non-linear.</div>

